The Heidelberg ThingstÃ¤tte is a relic of pre-war Nazi Germany built as a multipurpose amphitheater. Rooted in the Nordic tradition of public gatherings or "Things," the Nazi regime held propaganda presentations and rallies at this and other amphitheaters around Germany. Now, mostly reclaimed by nature, these sites are popular destinations for picnics, hikes, and, in the case of our visit, a rally for peace and love--in direct contrast to their original purpose.

The most ordinary-looking, grafittied metal bookcase standing in an alleyway is what you never knew you needed until it was standing right in front of you. 
I found the two books from my last post in here; luck had me there. 
And it makes me so genuinely happy to see that the book community can thrive on the simplest element: trust. A universal desire to share and obtain knowledge. A 'trust' that strangers will respect the bookcase and come back with some books of their own to share. It's a simple spirit; something that I think everyone can learn from. It gives me hope that there are still nice people left on this selfish planet.

Who else wishes there were more of these public street bookcases? 'cause I sure doğŸ˜­ğŸ™‹ğŸ»
